segments.text: This is Ed Hamlin here in El Paso, Texas, beginning an interview with Robert Parsons.
He spent some years with the city planning agency in El Paso prior to John Cunningham becoming the director.
Bob, how are you?
Just fine.
I actually went to work for the city of El Paso August 22, 1949, which is kind of prehistoric before Ed Hammond was born.
That's true, that's true.
But at the time that I went to work for the city, there had actually been one full-time person in the Department of Planning, a gentleman by the name of Walter E. Stockwell, who was involved in the
preparation of the original Kessler city plan in certain capacities.
His name appears in the report.
How long had he been planning director?
From about the time that the Kessler plan was adopted, which was quite a few years ago, he became the first planning director for the city.
Actually, city planning engineer was his title.
Shortly before I went to work for the city, two gentlemen were hired by a progressive mayor who thought that the city needed more than just one person to head its planning department.
And the first two were V.L.
Mike Mahoney, who came from Tucson and who was associated with Tucson planning department and later on was at Austin, and then from there on I kind of lost track of him.
He was a very accomplished, studious-type fellow who accomplished in the area of planning.
Along with him was William S. Bonner, who was with the Department of Planning in El Paso up until he went to University of Arkansas in Fayetteville.
So together, those two people and the director constituted the department.
That was the department.
Along about the first part of 1950,

independently and individually those two moved on to greener pastures and that was when i transferred into the department of planning working with mr stockwell from where i had been hired which was the department of public inspection of course i had an architectural background that sort of thing so it was kind of a natural gravitation and i worked with mr stockwell and performed all the functions of
preparing material and undertaking studies for the City Planning Commission and the Board of Adjustment, City Council, such things as that, for several years before I went into the Air Force in 1952.
I was involved in such lovely things as condemnation studies,
off-street parking, surveys, you know, the usual things you would expect to get into.
But with a small apartment, really two people, three people, we hired another person, you got to do everything, obviously, a little bit of everything.
Had to do a lot of original-type stuff.
comprehensive plan, or the plan that was originally adopted by the city, the Kessler plan, had that been updated during this period?
No.
Really, that was why Mike Mahoney and Bill Bonner were hired, to update the plan, which essentially had just been sitting there dormant for those many years.
They got into some of the earlier work on it, did part of the work, and then of course they moved on before it was really
really updated.
Portions of it were facelifted, about the best way you could say it.
But the city did have zoning authority at that time.
Yes.
In fact, zoning was practically the most of the plan that the city was following.
That was essentially it.
Describe El Paso during this period.
The post-war period was a period when we saw a lot of growth.
from the adoption of the Kessler Plan up until that time, we hadn't seen the kind of growth we've seen since then.
Describe how the city was composed and comprised, whether it had, in fact, outgrown the Kessler Plan or not.
Actually, the population of the city did not increase during the Kessler Plan, after the Kessler Plan was adopted, but in fact declined.
And this was partly because of the Depression and the economic conditions, and it was partly because of other circumstances.
It wasn't actually until after the war, or during the war, that the population came on back and drills began.
Of course, there was little subdivision activity and not an awful lot of development because of the war, during the war years.
But along about 49, well, from the late 40s on,
That's when the activity really began in the city, and it moved from a population of about 100,000 to a population of about 130,000 in the post-war years.
It had an area of about 25 square miles at that time, and much of the area within the city limit was undeveloped.
And if you relate it to
The city as it is now, along about Reynolds Avenue, was the end of the eastern growth of the city, which, of course, extends beyond that now probably, what, six or seven miles, seven or eight miles.
The Kessler plan as such didn't provide, it didn't really constitute a comprehensive plan as we'd consider it today.
And it specifically didn't provide a great deal of guidance in terms of land use and future arterials
in the outlying areas.
Would you agree with that or not?

It certainly was rather stylized at the time, but it did provide broad brushstrokes, things such as a park planning, a river walk, the McKelligan Canyon Park, a tunnel through the mountain, major thoroughfares planned.
A lot of the elements

of the city plan were incorporated in it, the unfortunate part was that very little of the plan was implemented during the period from when it was prepared and presented to the city up until it really became obsolescent.
I'm overstating this, but that's essentially it.
The plan was followed to a fair degree, but

not uh didn't always have the kind of support it should have had and certainly wasn't updated period on it a major function of the planning department since i've been aware of it has been the cartography section the preparation of base maps and preparation official city zoning maps and such what uh what kind of map documents existed at the time when you were with departments and how what role did the department have in the preparation of those maps
Practically none.
The city engineering department prepared maps and had the only cartography section that there really was.
The Department of Planning was principally, the personnel were engaged in planning more or less activities rather than the preparation of maps and this sort of thing.

did the planned commission provide more direction than perhaps it does today and on planning matters planned commission at that time consisted of five people who were rather than another large commission that we have now and it wasn't an attempt to represent a cross-section of every facet of the community it was selected of the prominent responsible
intelligent people who knew how to work together and wanted to work together on building a better community.
These people were not representing particular segments of the community, but they looked at themselves as representing the community as a whole.

and thought of the community as a whole in their activities that sounds like a bit of a contrast with some of the commissions we've had at least within my memory we have had a lot of growth in the city and during a period when we had at-large membership of the at-large elections of city council members frequently we found a lot of members of the city plan commission were
I mean, I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.
I think it's a good question.

uh knowledgeable in real estate but they were not earning their living from real estate or development the board of adjustment had realtors on it and people in the development area to give relief from the provisions of zoning ordinance but the planning commission took a little bit broader view with a little bit
that the leaders on the commission were looking at above and beyond the dollar sign, shall we say.
Today, the zoning board of adjustment, the staff assistance for the zoning board of adjustment is provided by the public inspection department.
What was the relationship between city planning and the zoning board of adjustment when you were with the department?
The department of planning provided the technical assistance to the board of adjustment.
The public inspection department was not involved in it.
This was thought that, well, if there was some question of construction that entered into it or something with the building code, they were invited in as guests.
But basically, the thinking at that time was that if there were flaws in the zoning ordinance that needed to be addressed,
the staff would be able to receive frequent requests for relief from evasions of the ordinance and could address the questions of the flaws more easily by dealing directly with it.
In other words, the commission did its thing, and then the Board of Adjustment did its thing, and the department provided the tie between.
How about in code enforcement of zoning provisions?
Essentially, the building department enforced the zoning ordinance.
Was there a good relationship between the planning department and the zoning and the billing official for that purpose?
Generally, yes.
Of course, the department provided technical assistance to the building official.
There was a feeling, probably not openly stated, that their job really was enforcement of the building code rather than the zoning ordinance.
And it was looked upon perhaps as a little bit on the orphan side, but there was good cooperation between the two sections.
During the period when you were with the department, were any of the ordinances changed, the zoning ordinance and the subdivision ordinance in particular?
At that time, there was not a subdivision ordinance as such.
It was subdivision regulations.
But as far as the zoning ordinance was concerned, oh, yes.

During that period of time, the first provisions for off-street parking and architectural control in certain zones and all the little refinements from the original zoning ordinance were constantly being incorporated and updated to meet the contemporary standards.

I'm interested in that from the standpoint the early plan documents, the Kessler plan and such, provided no specific guidelines with regard to provisions which are commonly incorporated in zoning ordinances, and yet it necessarily involves planning work, not necessarily comprehensive planning.
The determination of what is an appropriate setback and what is the appropriate density within a given zoning district, perhaps you could describe some of the thinking at the time.

that might have generated changes in the zoning ordinance well the regional zoning ordinance was prepared generally in accordance with the direction that was indicated in the city plan and it remained substantially intact during the 30s and then the first substantial updates were in the late late 30s and
And would these changes then be described as perhaps acknowledging more contemporary styles of development?
For instance, in the post-war era, the tract housing became increasingly common, and were you aware of changes that were made specifically to accommodate that kind of development?
The only thing that comes to mind were requirements for off-street parking.
And there were some changes made to the ordinance in the form of new districts in residential areas and apartment areas, which were more restrictive to reflect garden apartment type development.
to provide for wider side yards in a higher-grade residential than the old A Zone, so-called, which called for a fifty-foot lot and five-foot side yards.
There was a double A Zone that was created, which is larger lots and wider side yards and so on.
For the protection of the residences that were more significant in size.
Right.
In your area, that was the
the first change that occurred in tract development.
And, of course, the garden apartment type concept came in, and this also required more flexible use of land in the preparation of one- and two-story apartments, low density.
You mentioned parking standards were incorporated.
What existed prior to the thinking during that era in the way of parking standards?
The standard in El Paso was a 50-foot lot, as I mentioned, with a street in front and an alley in back and usually a detached garage opening in off of the alley.
With the post-war subdivision, the first thing that was limited, of course, in El Paso was the alley.
Streets were reduced in width.
Lots were increased in width and reduced slightly in depth.
And consequently, the only access was from the front.

And the first problems that we perceived in a growing community, growing family size and this sort of thing, was the single garage or the parking space that was provided on the site was often the first to go in order to accomplish a slightly increased
residents take care of new children, this sort of thing.
Filling in the garage.
Right.
And so we perceived that we were going to have to preserve off-street parking in some fashion on the site, or else enter into a period of chaos in your developing areas, which we did.
How about in commercial districts, the parking standards?
What existed prior to that?
Essentially nothing.
And this was left to the good development ideas of those making or constructing buildings in commercial areas.
This was probably commercial development was addressed later than residential, including apartment development.

off-street parking was easier to apply there on individual sites in connection with apartment development commercial came a little bit later and how was the implementation of parkinson as received by the development community so far as a residential apartment there's no problem at all so far as commercial was concerned there was a good deal of consternation
But it was quickly turned into acceptance when those developers realized that there was going to be, that the car was the most important thing they had to accommodate.
Post-war period saw a tremendous amount of infill development in El Paso's lower valley.
And today, it's not necessarily the most attractive area of the city, as we have a major arterial that runs the length of the valley that is lined with commercial businesses and such.
What was the thinking in terms of the planning for that area at the time?
Did the growth in that area outstrip the planned documents that were in effect?
The old arterial to which you refer is known as Alameda now.
And it was originally, or before that, it was US Highway 80.
And before that, it was State Highway 1.
So consequently, the creation of that facility predated any real planning in the area.
It was totally in the rural area.
An interesting facet of that, Texas adopted

a statute providing for subdivision regulation within five miles of the city limits which at one point in time was declared unconstitutional which rather clandestinely as far as el paso was concerned came came back on the books and for some period of time the
there was no planting beyond the city limits.
In other words, where the city limits stopped was where planting stopped for the community.
Consequently, the lower valley area you're talking about, if you're referring to, was largely developed without a plant.
The Oceanda Heights and the Ranchland Hills area, the lakeside and Miller's Lakeside, all these outlying subdivisions just sort of came into being
without a plan, and consequently you have offset streets, you have discontinuous streets, and you have rather poor circulation.

It is an area of the city that has a very inadequate thoroughfare plan today where it seems as though all the major arterials are running parallel to each other, and it makes it a problem to get around in.
And many of the arterials that enabled you to get around at all were created after the fact, expensively, at a later date, after planning came into the area.
Well, that seems to be an area that grew without much control.
There was an area to the north that's known generally as Cielo Vista, which has an interesting history in terms of some of its planning history.
Were you involved in any of that or aware of it?
Yes, the Department of Planning was involved in some of the earlier in-house master planning of the aerial.
This was originally called the Winfrey's Nose Tract.
It's just a big piece of land south of the airport that was owned by the federal government and acquired in connection with the airport facility.
was turned over to the airport for disposition, the proceeds of which were to go 100% into the improvement of the airport area.
The Department of Planning got into the act regarding the early disposition of a part of it.
There was a reluctance to hire consultants to do the work.
So consequently, the department was kind of pressed into
into service to provide some orderly disposal and development of it.
The area between Montana and Edgemere, to a large degree, was planned by consulting engineers working for the private developers who purchased the earlier sections of the land.
Later on, we were successful in the later stages of it, getting the airport to hire a consultant to master plan most of the remaining area.
In fact, all the remaining area, both as to orderly disposition on a timely basis,
and master planning streets and parks and schools and other facilities that would normally be in a large subdivision area.
So the city took on a role beyond simply the preparation of a general plan document, but preparing a rather specific master plan in that area.
In the earlier stages, this is correct.
Was it pretty faithfully implemented?
Oh, yes.
Yes.
It was both the city's part in the coordination

of the earlier subdivisions and then in the after the master plan was actually closely on down to the to the southernmost portion of it which was impacted to a degree by the freeway interstate 10 which was developed after
the whole master plan was actually adopted.

Today, when we think about the southeast part of the city, we refer generally to the area between Montana Avenue and Interstate 10, and Interstate 10 is the driving force for much of that development.
The period when you worked for the department, Interstate 10 didn't exist, and its alignment hadn't been determined, and perhaps even the concept of what a freeway is was not fully understood.
Can you describe that for me?

Yes, the Department of Transportation, well, Texas Highway Department at the time, knew that there ultimately would be a freeway coming through the El Paso area, but they weren't sure what a freeway was or what size it was.
They had no criteria for a freeway.
So the Department of Planning, working with the Highway Department, designated what's now known as Edgemere Drives
as the future location of the freeway.
It paralleled Montana Street.
It was 200 feet wide.
It incorporated as much as at that time, which was before any freeways were actually constructed.
As a matter of fact, the formal document that we had to go on was a study that was prepared back in 1940.
which referred to interregional highways prepared by the federal government.
That was kind of the Bible, but it didn't really tell much about what a freeway was going to look like.

So consequently, we designated this 200-foot strip as a reserved area so that we wouldn't get the area cut off totally and require a lot of demolition of structures in order to get this freeway through.
Later on, it was determined this was totally inadequate.
It was not properly located.

And the Highway Department's actual location for Interstate 10 was from a half a mile to several miles south and not parallel to Montana, but more or less dividing equally the area between the river and Montana.
You mentioned a while ago that a lot of the highway facilities seem to parallel one another.
This is true, but then the way El Paso is, the configuration, the squeeze between Mexico and the south
the mountain that pokes down in the middle of it, and the military reservation that takes a big hunk out of the northeast section.
So really and truly, we have a thoroughfare system that kind of wanders around between these fixed facilities.
And that's the direction that traffic has to move, and that's the way the facilities are built.
And they do end up, many facilities, more or less parallel.
The period between 1950 and 1960 saw the city better than double in population from about 130,000 to over 270,000.
There was a lot of growth and change.
From your perception, describe what the community, describe that period of growth and what it meant to the community and where it came from.
OK.
I was absent from the community from 52 to 56 when I was in the,
Air Force during the Korean festivities.
When I left in 1952, June the 9th, the Department of Planning consisted of three people.
The community was growing.
When I came back in 1956, the Department of Planning had grown to about seven or eight people.
The former director, Mr. Stockwell, had retired.
We had a new planning director, Loudon Lingo,
And we had really begun more fully the planning process.
There was some money being committed to capital improvements on a fairly regular basis each year with the budget.
Consequently, the planning was beginning to come into its own.
The large growth you referred to came about primarily because of
what so many people had discovered in the Southwest as to climate, as to interest in the area and the charm of the area.

And there was an awful lot of returning GIs, people who had been stationed here, who had been assigned here for a period of time, and the military as civilians coming back into the community made the biggest impact and the biggest part of that growth.
along with industrial development in the area.
In the pre-war period, Juarez was a sleepy community, and El Paso was the dominant community, at least twice the size of Juarez.
As El Paso grew, it continued to outpace the growth of Juarez for a period of time.
It's interesting because Oahuas today is probably two and a half times the size of El Paso.
Easily.
And, of course, this is largely due to the economic situation and the migration to the north and across the border.
The, I would say, migration to the north and the whole trend of urbanization, the rural population migrating to the cities, I suppose, is contributing to the growth of Oahuas.
Well, most of the growth of wars, obviously, is due to the fact that it offers some hope of migration to the United States, and twin-plan concepts, and so on, so on, so on.
Well-known.
During that period, you mentioned a lot of the Wingo.
